<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-10T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-10T08:00:00-05:00" n="187" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d187">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/10406</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-10T13:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">October 10, 1918, 1 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 11, 3
                                    p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2704. War Trade Board [from <persName>Frothingham</persName>]:</p>
                            <p>No. 1639. <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_FPj1">Fuller</persName>. Your 1274, Department’s 1626, September 26.
                                Action in Portuguese matter has been delayed by lack of reply from
                                French Minister of Blockade and have telegraphed
                                    <persName>Stetson</persName> in Paris to press the matter in
                                view of peace overtures from Berlin. Feeling here is that every
                                effort should be made to speed up liquidation of enemy firms in
                                Allied countries. Proposed withdrawal of stat[utory] list Portugal
                                should be accelerated if at that price more rapid liquidation enemy
                                firms could be secured.<note n="1" xml:id="d187fn1">Last sentence is
                                    as corrected by telegram No. 2837 from Great Britain, received
                                    October 17 (File No. 763.72112/10463).</note>
                                <persName>Frothingham</persName>.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>